1. Dish Overview

Flavor Profile: salty, sweet, umami, acidic

Texture Goals: blistered, rendered wing skin with internal meat temperature of 74°C / 165°F; sauce viscosity coating wings at 0.5–1 mm thickness

What Makes This Version Exceptional:
Controlled thermal rendering of skin in the air fryer followed by stovetop reduction of the honey–garlic glaze creates Maillard-driven umami depth while preventing sauce scorching and skin softening from premature glazing.

⸻

2. Ingredients

Protein
	•	Chicken wings, separated into flats and drumettes: 900 g / 2 lb
	•	Fine sea salt: 6 g / 1 tsp
	•	Ground black pepper: 2 g / 1/2 tsp

Sauce
	•	Honey: 40 g / 2 tbsp
	•	Soy sauce (regular): 30 ml / 2 tbsp
	•	Garlic, finely minced: 12 g / 4 cloves
	•	Rice vinegar: 10 ml / 2 tsp
	•	Neutral oil: 15 ml / 1 tbsp

Garnish
	•	Green onion, thinly sliced: 10 g / 2 tbsp

⸻

3. Equipment / Tools / Skills

Required Equipment:
Air fryer, saucepan, tongs, mixing bowl, chef’s knife, cutting board, instant-read thermometer

Techniques Involved:
Air frying, seasoning, reduction, sautéing, glazing

Skill Level Assumptions:
Ability to season evenly, control stovetop heat during reduction, verify internal poultry temperature, and coordinate parallel cooking tasks.

⸻

4. Mise en Place
	•	Pat chicken wings completely dry; separate joints if needed.
	•	Measure all sauce ingredients precisely.
	•	Mince garlic to fine, uniform particles (≤2 mm).
	•	Preheat air fryer to 200°C / 390°F for 3 minutes.

⸻

5. Step-by-Step Instructions

I. Season wings with salt and pepper; toss to distribute evenly. This ensures uniform ionic penetration before heat application.
II. Arrange wings in a single layer in the air fryer basket. Air fry at 200°C / 390°F for 12 minutes.
III. Flip wings and continue air frying at 200°C / 390°F for 8–10 minutes until skin is blistered and internal temperature reaches 74°C / 165°F (±1°C).
IV. While wings cook, heat saucepan on stovetop over medium heat (170–180°C / 340–355°F surface temperature). Add neutral oil and garlic; sauté for 30–45 seconds until aromatic without browning.
V. Add honey, soy sauce, and rice vinegar. Reduce heat to low and simmer 3–4 minutes until glaze thickens to coating consistency; avoid boiling to prevent sugar scorching.
VI. Transfer cooked wings to saucepan. Toss with glaze for 30–45 seconds off heat to coat evenly without further reduction.
VII. Rest wings for 2 minutes to allow glaze adhesion and internal moisture equilibration.

⸻

6. Critical Technique Notes
	•	Skin softening: Applying sauce before air frying traps moisture; always glaze after crisping.
	•	Sugar scorching: Excess heat during reduction causes bitterness; recover by adding 5–10 ml water and reheating gently.
	•	Food safety: Verify internal temperature at the thickest wing section.
	•	Flavor flatness risk: Insufficient acidity reduces balance; correct by adding rice vinegar in 2 ml increments.

⸻

7. Plating & Serving

Arrange wings in a shallow bowl with minimal overlap. Garnish with green onion.
Target service temperature: 65–70°C / 150–160°F.
Texture contrast: crisp skin against viscous glaze.
First dominant flavor: sweet.
Final persisting flavor: umami.

⸻

8. Make-Ahead / Storage
	•	Sauce may be prepared up to 48 hours in advance; refrigerate at ≤4°C / 40°F.
	•	Cooked wings store up to 24 hours refrigerated.
	•	Reheat wings in air fryer at 190°C / 375°F for 4–5 minutes; do not re-sauce until reheated.

⸻

9. Optional Refinements (Clearly Optional)
	•	Add 2 g / 1/2 tsp grated fresh ginger to sauce during garlic sauté for aromatic expansion.
	•	Finish glaze with 5 g / 1 tsp unsalted butter off heat for fat-phase aroma release.
	•	Briefly torch glazed wings (≤5 seconds total) to reactivate surface sugars before service.